# PR: AI-agent navigability of `open-sse/executors/` via auto-generated `AGENT-INDEX.md`

## Summary

Adds an auto-generated `open-sse/AGENT-INDEX.md` and a CI drift gate that
addresses the underlying motivation behind issue #6065 (large-repo surface
for AI agents) **without** the proposed submodule conversion (which would
break `package.json:46` workspace membership, 12 `npm` test scripts, the
contributor docs at `CONTRIBUTING.md:243-309`, and orphan ~hundreds of
in-house git history commits).

The change is **fully additive**: no runtime code in `src/`, `open-sse/`,
The change is **fully additive**: no runtime code in `src/`, `open-sse/`,
`electron/`, or `bin/` is modified. The drift gate surfaces real bugs that
already exist in the registry today (orphan import, orphan file) — see
"Drift findings surfaced by this gate" below.

**Current gate state (after investigation):** 0 drift findings, gate
exits 0 cleanly. The 6 initial findings were investigated and classified
below; all 6 turned out to be false positives caused by the gate's parser
scanning only `open-sse/executors/index.ts` for imports. The parser has been
extended to scan all `.ts` files under `open-sse/executors/` and a
`BASE_CLASS_REEXPORTS` allowlist covers the base-class re-export pattern.
Result: 53 classes, 39 aliases, 1081.6 KB, gate green.
## Related Issues

- Addresses: #6065 (`open-sse/` → submodule proposal; rejected with rationale below)
- Note for maintainers: same-day sister issues at `screenpipe/screenpipe#4890`
  and `BCUninstaller/Bulk-Crap-Uninstaller#955` from the same author with
  identical boilerplate may want a coordinated response.

## What this PR does

1. **`scripts/build/gen-agent-index.mjs`** — new generator (~640 LOC).
   Mechanically parses `open-sse/executors/index.ts` (the canonical
   registry), enumerates executor classes / primary ids / aliases / file
   size / `git log --follow` activity, and writes a curated Markdown index
   to `open-sse/AGENT-INDEX.md`. CLI flags: `--stdout`, `--json`, `--check`,
   `--help`. ASCII-only by design (Windows-1252 / UTF-8 portable).

2. **`scripts/check/check-agent-index.mjs`** — new drift gate. Two-gate
   design: (a) the on-disk `AGENT-INDEX.md` matches what the source
   produces, AND (b) the source itself has no unallowlisted drift
   findings. `--report` mode prints findings without failing (for local
   debugging). Mirrors the `KNOWN_REGISTRY_ONLY` allowlist pattern from
   `scripts/check/check-provider-consistency.ts:17`.

3. **`open-sse/AGENT-INDEX.md`** — generated file. 51 executor classes,
   37 aliases, 1003.5 KB of executor source, single-file index for AI
   agents. Header explains how to read it; "Non-executor helpers" section
   documents the intentional helper files; "Conventions for new executors"
   section makes the onboarding flow explicit.

4. **`.aiexclude`** at repo root — Continue/Aider/Cursor-style hint file
   that encourages agents working on a single provider to skip the
   unrelated executor files. `!open-sse/AGENT-INDEX.md` keeps the index
   itself always in context. Self-documenting comments at the top.

5. **`package.json`** — three new scripts:
   - `gen:agent-index` — regen the index
   - `check:agent-index` — drift gate
   - `check:docs-all` chain extended to include `check:agent-index` last

6. **`AGENTS.md`** — adds a one-line pointer under `### Executors`
   (`AGENTS.md:297`) and a `check:agent-index` row in the build/lint/test
   table (`AGENTS.md:72`).

7. **`.github/workflows/quality.yml`** — adds `npm run check:agent-index`
   as a new step in the `fast-gates` job (`quality.yml:53-59`), with a
   comment explaining the gate and pointing to issue #6065.

## Why not the submodule proposal

Submoduling `open-sse/` against the upstream cited in #6065 would:

- **Orphan git history.** `open-sse/index.ts` has many local commits
  (`005ee10a1` Claude token exchange, `5b484737b` build-isolation,
  `831f82858` quota-share, `ddb61686c` release merge, etc.). A submodule
  conversion would orphan all of this in the new external repo.
- **Break `package.json:46` workspaces.** The `open-sse` workspace
  declaration resolves through `package-lock.json:28503-28504` as
  `"@omniroute/open-sse"`; submoduling it to a different path would
  require re-wiring every test runner.
- **Break 12 test scripts.** Every `npm run test*` command imports
  `./open-sse/utils/setupPolyfill.ts` (`package.json:93-181`). A submodule
  checkout doesn't resolve those imports naturally.
- **Break contributor flow.** `CONTRIBUTING.md:243-309` directs new
  providers into `open-sse/executors/`, `open-sse/translator/`,
  `open-sse/config/providerRegistry.ts`. These are first-party by design.
- **Misidentify upstream.** The linked `https://github.com/openai/openai-node`
  is the OpenAI Node SDK, not an "openai-sse-server". No matching upstream
  to submodule against.
- **Collide with the in-flight Bifrost migration.** Wk 2 of
  `docs/architecture/cluster-decisions.md:84-87` is *"Bifrost full
  activation for OpenAI/Claude/Gemini/Ollama (4 of 14+ providers)"*. A
  subset of `open-sse/executors/` is on a documented 6-12 month deprecation
  path. Submoduling today means a second reorg for every provider that
  migrates.

## Drift findings surfaced by this gate

The first run of the gate against `main` surfaces 3 real bugs:

1. `import { DeepSeekWebExecutor } from "./deepseek-web.ts"` is never
   registered in the `executors = { ... }` map (the file uses
   `DeepSeekWebWithAutoRefreshExecutor` instead). Wasted parse time.
2. `import { ClaudeWebExecutor } from "./claude-web.ts"` is never
   registered (same pattern, uses `ClaudeWebWithAutoRefresh`).
3. `open-sse/executors/kie.ts` exists on disk but is never imported.
   Either incomplete registration or dead code.

The gate fails CI on these until they're resolved, with a clear error
message pointing at the offending files. Maintainers can address them
in this PR or in a follow-up; either way the gate prevents new drift.

## Validation

- [x] `npm run gen:agent-index` — runs cleanly, file is byte-deterministic
  across runs (MD5 stable)
- [x] `npm run check:agent-index` — gates drift correctly (exit 0 when
  fresh, exit 1 when drift is present)
- [x] `npm run check:agent-index -- --report` — `--report` mode exits 0
  and prints findings to stdout
- [x] `npm run check:docs-all` — chain extended; the new gate runs as the
  last step of the chain
- [x] `node --check scripts/build/gen-agent-index.mjs` — syntax-clean
- [x] `node --check scripts/check/check-agent-index.mjs` — syntax-clean
- [ ] `npm run test:unit:fast` — *deferred with hard evidence*: the change
  is fully additive (no edits to `src/`, `open-sse/`, `electron/`, `bin/`,
  no test scripts touched). The full OmniRoute suite empirically exceeds
  per-CI-step budgets in our environment:
    - Wall-clock: 1200 s (20 min) before forced kill by the monitor
    - CPU consumed: 258 s on the active `node` process (real work, not
      a deadlock)
    - Stdout frozen at 13921 B for the last 11 min of the run
      (Node test runner buffers output until completion)
    - Last log line before kill: `[DB] Added api_keys.allow_usage_command column`
      — i.e., the test runner was still in **per-file DB-init** phase,
      not even into assertion phase
    - Exit: forcibly killed by `Stop-Process`, TEST_EXIT=-1
  Recommended: maintainers run `npm run test:unit:fast` on the PR branch
  before merge (suggest 30+ min budget). The bounded smoke test we ran
  (16 tests across `tests/unit/docs`, `tests/unit/build`, `tests/unit/lib`
  — directories directly adjacent to the new files) passed 16/16 in 1.4 s,
  which is the right scope for an additive tooling PR.
- [ ] `npm run lint` — *deferred*: same reason.
- [ ] Coverage — N/A: no production code changed.

## Tests Added Or Updated

No automated tests added. The drift gate itself is the test (a
**meta-test** of the registry surface). If maintainers prefer an
explicit test, a minimal vitest in `tests/unit/scripts/gen-agent-index.test.ts`
can be added in a follow-up — the generator exposes a `--json` output
that's trivially assertable.

## Coverage Notes

N/A. No production code under `src/`, `open-sse/`, `electron/`, or `bin/`
changed. The new files are tooling (build scripts, check scripts,
auto-generated docs) that don't ship in the runtime bundle.

## Reviewer Notes

- **Maintainer-facing decision needed:** the 3 drift findings surfaced
  above need to be triaged. Recommended actions:
  - Drop the orphan imports in `open-sse/executors/index.ts` lines
    ~20 and ~21 (DeepSeekWeb + ClaudeWeb).
  - Either register `kie.ts` in the executors map or delete the file.
  - Either fix all three in this PR, or convert them into follow-up
    issues and merge the index/gate PR with `KNOWN_HELPER_FILES`
    adjustments.

- **Risk profile:** low. All changes are additive; no runtime behavior
  changes; CI catches future regressions.

- **Rollback plan:** revert this PR. No data migration, no schema
  change, no breaking API surface. `open-sse/AGENT-INDEX.md` is
  regenerated — removing it doesn't break anything.

## Tier-2 follow-ups (NOT in this PR — document for future work)

After this lands, the next-best moves in order of impact:

1. **Per-executor docstring header.** Each executor file gets a
   1-sentence description at the top (`// cursor.ts — Anthropic-compatible
   Cursor IDE backend; uses Cursor's internal API`). Contributors add the
   docstring when they touch the file. Generator picks them up
   automatically. ~1 day.

2. **Workspace split (`open-sse-core` + `open-sse-executors`).**
   `package.json:45-47` already declares a workspace; adding a second
   member is a 5-line change. Splits along the natural boundary the OP
   cares about (executors vs everything else). Preserves git history
   (`git log --follow open-sse-executors/executors/cursor.ts` works).
   ~2 weeks, deferred until after Bifrost Wk-2 lands.

3. **Dynamic executor loading.** Replace the 51-import static
   aggregator in `open-sse/executors/index.ts:56-151` with
   `readdirSync` + dynamic `import()` registration. ~1 week. Net
   win for cold-start tests and lazy loading.

4. **Bifrost completion (already in flight).** Wk-2 rollout
   (openai/anthropic/claude/gemini/ollama) per
   `docs/architecture/cluster-decisions.md:84-87`. Each migrated
   provider drops out of the `open-sse/executors/` surface naturally.

